- - - ( Fetch Modes and Methods ) - - - 



** ( The 2 Fetch Methods ):

• ( fetch() ):
  Fetches the next single row from the result set.
  Returns false if no more rows.

• ( fetchAll() ):
  Fetches all remaining rows in the result set into an array.
  Returns an empty array if no rows.



** ( List of Fetch Mdoes ):

• ( PDO::FETCH_ASSOC ):
  Returns an associative array indexed by column names.

• ( PDO::FETCH_NUM ):
  Returns a numeric array indexed by column position (0, 1, 2...).

• ( PDO::FETCH_BOTH (default if not changed) ):
  Returns both associative and numeric keys.

• ( PDO::FETCH_OBJ ):
  Returns results as an anonymous object, with column names as properties.

• ( PDO::FETCH_CLASS ):
  Maps results into a user-defined class (properties filled by column names).

• ( PDO::FETCH_INTO ):
  Populates an existing object instance with column values.

• ( PDO::FETCH_COLUMN ):
  Returns only a single column value (e.g., just IDs).

• ( PDO::FETCH_KEY_PAIR ):
  Returns an associative array: first column = key, second column = value.

• ( PDO::FETCH_GROUP ):
  Groups rows by the first column, values are arrays of remaining columns.

• ( PDO::FETCH_UNIQUE ):
  Returns rows keyed by the first column, discarding duplicates.

• ( PDO::FETCH_FUNC ):
  Calls a user-defined function on each row and returns the result.